    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "## Problem\n\nThe autocmds defined here:\n\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/adb5d8a6460b9005c870467f4dc962278b708a8f/runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic/_store.lua#L11-L19\n\nand here:\n\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/adb5d8a6460b9005c870467f4dc962278b708a8f/runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic/_store.lua#L49-L55\n\nare extremely \"noisy\" (they define a handler for *every* buffer that is \"touched\", even if it's never loaded)\n\nin a session where i've done lots of quickfix work, `:autocmd` shows 5000+ autocmd definitions:\n\n```\nBufReadPost\n    <buffer=23>\n              <Lua 358: /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic/_store.lua:56>\n    <buffer=24>\n              <Lua 360: /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic/_store.lua:56>\n    <buffer=25>\n...\n\nnvim.diagnostic.buf_wipeout  BufWipeout\n    <buffer=631>\n              <Lua 2951: /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic/_store.lua:20>\n    <buffer=632>\n              <Lua 2913: /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic/_store.lua:20>\n    <buffer=633>\n```\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nNot sure if this a performance issue or just a UI issue.\n\n- If it's only a UI issue, then maybe we can \"group\" things better in the default output of `:autocmd`. And `:verbose autocmd` could show the full details.\n    - But that may be a step backwards, because it hides potential problems. So it should perhaps show a warning/error highlight when an autocmd exceeds a threshold.\n    - And/or, we should find a different approach for `_store.lua`.\n- There is a *display performance* issue when displaying 20_000+ `:autocmd` lines: with ui2 it takes 2+ seconds, without ui2 it's instant.\n\ncc @faergeek ",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "To clarify, in a session where you've done a lot of quickfix work you're also setting diagnostics from quickfix, right? Otherwise these `BufRead` autocmds shouldn't have been created.\n\nI can't really think of another alternative to creating a bunch of `BufRead` autocmds in such cases other than forcefully loading these buffers and setting extmarks right away. It seems like this would be worse in terms of performance though as we would need to load potentially a lot of buffers in memory, which then can never be actually opened by the user, so all that time and memory is wasted.\n\nFor `BufWipeout` I think we could probably store that cache in a buffer variable instead, so they're freed automatically without needing an autocmd. Most usages of that cache seem to be concerned about a particular buffer, except when `get_diagnostics` is called with no `bufnr` here:\n\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/adb5d8a6460b9005c870467f4dc962278b708a8f/runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic/_store.lua#L147-L163\n\nIt would need to iterate over all loaded buffers and collect their variables instead. In case of lots of buffers for which diagnostics were never set it would be worse since current implementation explicitly iterates over only buffers for which either diagnostics were set or some code has attempted to access them for some reason (empty tables are created in `__index`).",
